Pitt revamps Web site

MREHAN NASIR
Editor in Chief

/

Thousands of helpful Web sites are
available everyday to students, from
online textbooks to ‘trip planning and
sports information. But for Pitt students,
the best may be the University’s own
Pitt.edu site. 4 ’ _

The site recently changed _to include
brighter colors and larger pictures. It also
has simpler links and category names for
easier navigation. _ ' A

“The Web site is a work in progress,”
said Robert Hill, executive director of
public affairs at‘Pitt.

He said the site has been under con-
struction since October.

Students are able to look up almost
anything Pitt-related on the site, from
faculty names and e-mail addresses to
links to Pitt sports. ‘Information about
housing and food services is also online,

along with the complete University fact V

books from the past four years.

Hill saidvthat a -committee from the
provost’s office had been selected to look
at the old site and suggest improvements.

“We looked at quite a few other uni-
versities,” said John Cooper, the Web-
master for the_ site. “That way we got a

' sense of what did and didn’t wor .”

Pitt’s ofﬁce of public affairs handled
the site’s content and added news head-

lines and events on the top of the home
page. To clearly identify the site as Pitt’s,
the blue and gold were darkened and a
larger seal and photo of the Cathedral of
Learning were used. Many of the photos
on the site have also been updated, and a
virtual campus tour can be taken online.

Halo Technologies from Pittsburgh
is helping Pitt with part of the site,
including template ‘creation for the grad-
uate recruitment sections.

Jinx -Walton and Brian Hart from
Computing Services and Systems
Development handled the technical

aspects of the new site, including putting

the new site online. CSSD will a1so.han-
dle the server maintenance.

Hill said that although the new site
was planned to be unveiled this past
spring, the committee was delayed

because of the time it took to get a con-.

sensus from all the parties involved. 4'

The old site has been up since; 1996'
and rarely changed, according to Cooper. 4 '
“Now that the new site is "under [pub- 5

lic affairs], we’ll be able to keep it up
with emerging technologies. Obviously
it’ll evolve along with everything else,”
he said. 1 * A

