chalking cars is not the answer

to Oak|and’s parking problem

Most of us car owners are very

‘protective of our dear autos. We talk to ‘

our cars, give them names and wash
them lovingly on a serni-regular basis.

. And usually we don’t like it when

strangers touch them.

So at ﬁrst glance the Oakland
Business Improvement Dist1ict’s initia-
tive of chalking tires on cars parked at
meters seems a bit invasive. According
to this plan, the chalking is necessary so
that the Pittsburgh Parking Authority
can check up on the cars to make sure
that people are. not extending the time
limits ‘by, feeding the meters.

, While the idea of someone com-
ing at your car with a stick of white
powdery stuff when you haven’t even
done anything wrong is not desirable, it
isforgivable. Chalk washes off. What’s
worse about this initiative is that it’s a
short-term solution at best, and not a
very good one at that.

‘OBID’s,intention, it seems, is to
prevent people from using the meters

. as all-day parking spots in an effort to

free up more space for shoppers and
restaurant patrons. But it seems doubt-

, ful that the chalking will really solve I

the problem.
Picture the scenario — your meter
has expired, your tires are chalked and,

_ not knowing where else to park, you

are very sad and desperate. As the tears
of frustration begin to fall, lo and
behold, you spot another parking spot‘

across the street and back a few feet.
You artfully maneuver into the space,
pop in your quarters" and revel in your
parking security until the drama begins
again in two hours. .

Thus parking in Oakland becomes
a big rollicking game of musical chairs,
in which spots are never actually freed
and everyone is hassled.

There is one obvious long-term
solution to this problem — more park-

«ing lots and garages in Oakland. Over

the past few years, Pitt seemed to pri-
oritize building more student housing.
It’s time for that focus to shift to creat-
ing more parking space. .

The Multipurpose Academic
Complex on Forbes Avenue, currently
under construction, is,being built to
include a sub-ground parking garage.
This will certainly help but won’t be
enough. More drastic and potentially
expensive measures may be requisite
— i.e., building multiple layers above
or below the parking lot situated
between the Hillman and ‘Carnegie
libraries, or razing a few decrepit hous-
es in South Oakland. ’ —

It remains to be seen as to whether
OBlD’s plan will actually increase
business; yet it can be certain that the
scheme  multiply headaches and
frazzled nerves ‘in many a driver. OBID

and Pitt, either independently or jointly, .

should begin investigating the ‘afore-
mentioned permanent solutions.

 

