“Christians are evil!” _ .

I was taken aback when, a few years ago, my
friend Sean blurted out that statement over lunch.
Being a‘ ‘gay man, Sean was keenly aware of the
fact that many Christians selectively quote from
the Bible in an attempt to justify anti-gay bigotry.
But his statement was an unfair generalization,
and I called him ‘on it. We got into a heated argu-
ment, and ended up not speaking to -
each other for some time.

Ironically Sean, in generalizing
all Christians as anti-gay bigots,
himself engaged in prejudicial
stereotyping. That type of rhetoric is
wrong, no matter the target. ‘

A further irony of Sean’s statement is that
many out—and-proud lesbians and gay men are
devout practicing Christians.-More_over, many of
these gay Christians are passionate and articulate
crusaders for the gay rights movement.

I met one of these exemplary gay Christians

. way back in the spring of 1989, when I was an

undergraduate student at the State University of
New York at Buifalo. Darlene Gamer, who at
that time served on the Philadelphia rnayor’s
Commission on Sexual Minorities, was invited

I that semester to speak at my school as part of our

Black History Month program.

Gamer — a black lesbian mother and grand-
mother as well as a Christian clergywoman ——
made a powerful impression on me and the other
students. One of the interesting comments she

. made was that she was bothered by the presence

of ecclesiophobia —— a fear of churches and reli-
gion — within the lesbian and gay community. ‘

To a degree, such ecclesiophobia is under-
standable. After all, when anti-gay religious big-
ots such as Gary Bauer and Pat Robertson spend
so much time hogging the media spotlight,’it can
sometimes seem like Christianity and homopho-
bia are hopelessly intertwined.‘

But as Gamer noted that evening in Buffalo,

misguided Christians have also attempted to‘

yoke white supremacy, male chauvinism and

— other evils to their religion. Like today’s anti-gay

